{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn84024808/00295860716/1920120901/0238.xml":{"full_text":"GREAT FALLS DAILY TRIBUNE\nW. M. Bole, Editor O S. Warden. Manager^ Leon ard G. Pie kt, Business Manag er\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nThe Business Outlook\nIT is a time for sane and calm dis\ncussion of the business situation.\nThe business outlook is being dis\ncussed on the streets, in the clubs,\nin the banks and in the business of\nfices of businessmen every day. It\nmight as well be disucssed in the col\numns of the newspapers, especially\nas the business situation is much\nsounder than the fears and hysteria\nof some portion o\u00a3 the community\nwould make it. To attempt to dis\nguise the fa't that there is more de\nmand for cr-dit in the world, not ex\ncepting the United States, than there\nis available supply would be foolish.\nEveryone knows money and credit\nis at a premium.When a country\nlike Norway with no great debt and\nmuch available property offers bet\nter than eight per cent for a loan of\ntwenty million dollars in New York\nit. is needless to deny that money is\nscarce and high priced in Europe.\nWhen the Anaconda Copper company\noffers its first mortgage bonds for\nan insignificant sum compared with\nthe value of the property covered\nby th\"sc bonds and they sell on a\nbasis that means about eight per cent\nto the purchaser it is useless to deny\nthat the home demand is greater than\nthe supply. When these conditions\nare prient commodity prices go down\nand money prices go up in accord\nwith the universal law of supply and\nwith the universal law of supply and\ndemand. This is oniy another way\nof stating the fact that when many\nowners of commodities bid against\neach other for n short supply of cash\nor credit, the tendency is to give\nmore and more of these commodities\nto get a dollar. Then prices fall and\ninterest rates go up and\nan '\"appreciating dollar, that is on 1\nthat buys more commodities than be\nfore That is what is going on now.\nhave had the same experience\nwe have\nWe\nbefore. We have had it far worse\nthan we h^ve it at the present, with\naccompanying pani-and general bus\niness disaster.\nFortunately, conditions warrant no\nsuch expectation at present. The\ncountry is rich in commodities that\nthe world stands in need of. We\nhave produced more food this year\nthan we ever did before. There i\nplenty to feed ail our population and\nleave la'ge surplus to feed the hun\ngry in other parts of the world. Our\nbanking system is sound. We have\nhad practically no bank failure- in\nthe United States of any importance.\nInd' ed, if we except a very few\nsmall country bank- which over-ex- I\ntended themselves in discounting the\nfarmers' paper we can say that we\nhave had none at all. Likewise, the\nbusiness failure\u00ab are comparatively\ntew and insignificant. No, big busi\nncss houses have gone down in the\nlast nine months. This, in view of\nthe falling values of merchandise\nwhich in many ca>es has represented\nlosses to merchants and manufactur\ners who bought or manufactured <>n\na higher price level, is cenlinly\na very encouraging fact. The fed\neral reserve bank system has func\ntioned splendidly and wisely. They\nhave helped to tide us over the pain\nful process of contraction in value^\nwith wisdom and sound judgment,\npaying no heed to hysterical appeal\nnot founded ou s<>und business prin\nciples, and yet doin 1 their duty man\nfully in financing business, agricul\nfully in financing business, agricul\nture and the productive forces of the\ncountry.\nThe contraction of values or fall\ning prices through which we are now\ngoing is a painful proc\u00e8s*, but a nee\nessary one for the health of the body\npolitic. Not long ago every one was\ndenouncing high prices and calling\non the government to take action to\nbring them down. The government\nresponded to the call and did what\nit could in that respect. We all re\nmember the efforts, and that they\ndid not have any great effect. Prices\nwent soaring upward in spite of sales\n\"f war sto< ks at less than cost and\nprosecutions for profiteering. Gov\nernmental action to bring down the\nprices of necessities of life was rath\ner futile on the whole though it may\nhave done some good. The cost of\nliving, urged on by immutable econ\nomic law, kept climbing still notwith\nstanding. Now the cry is reversed.\nThe government is asked to use it\"\npower to boost the price of commod\nities-because they have fallen to a\npoint below the cost of production.\nPerhaps it will again respond and do\nwhat it can to boost present prices,\nor at least to retard their further\ndecline. We don't think it will ac\ncomplish much more than it did when\nit sought the reverse action. So far\nas it can help we hope it will, be\ncause the fall in prices has been too\nswift for the prosperity and economic\ngood of the nation, and a great\nhardship on our producers, many\nof whom are discouraged by their\nexperience and inclined to cease pro\nduction or at least curtail it largely.\nThat in turn will be a very bad t|ting\nfor us and induce harder times and\nmore loss.\nBut we are glad to note every sign\nthat induces optimism and as we see\nit th^re are a good many signs that\nthe bottom of falling prices has been\ntouched and an upward trend may\nsoo\u00bb be looked for. The role of the\nprophet in economic futures is a ris\nky one and we feel our own lack of\nknowledge and vision and wisdom\ntoo keenly to risk attempting such a\nrole, yet we find others with greater\nconfidence in their insight into the\nfuture and better qualified as experts\nwho take the view that the worst is\novr in falling prices, and brighter\ndays are ahead for the merchant and\nproducer. And right here we pause\nto say that their interest is identical\nand there is no profit to be made by\nthe\ndeprived of hi\nknow that the statement may awaken\ndebate and dissent.\nThe Harvard University commit\ntee o\" economic research is the pro\nphet who foretells a better and a\nbrighter day, and they have the dis\nThis committee has issued a state\nment on the first of the present\nmonth as it has done every three\nmonths for some time past. The\n1 most cheering part of its present pre\nj diction is that by next April the pre\nsent recession in business will have\nj ended and an upward movement will\nmonths is the inauguration of price\nrecessions among the basic commod\nmtddlem- n while the producer is\nprofit, though we\ntinction of havin\" n-edicted correct\nunction oi na^in\u201e preaicteci correct\nly th'- course of prices in the past,\nbegin. It says:\n\"We find no reason in re<ent de\nvelopments to change the forecast of\nOctober 15 that we 'have passed the\ntime in the business cycle when a\nI financial panic would have occurred,\n'.f we were to have one,\" and that\nthe out!o\"k for the next three to six\niries heretofore unaffected, the ex\ntension of price revision* to retail\n\nmarkets, an increase in the number\nof business failures, easier money as\nthe result of the release of credit\nby liquidation in commodity markets,\nand an increase of security prices.'\n1 r\nFurther, recent movements of the\nc urves or o 1 'r i'*dcx clis- support\nthe forecast that \"the recession of\nbusiness, now in progress, will termi\nnate by April. 1921.\"\nBut we do not need to rely solely\nexpectation that\nthe business man\non the economic experts of Harvard\ncollege for the\nbrighter days lor\nare near at hand. Our leading bank\n\"rs and the captains of industry\nnearly all express the same view.\nThe recessions in prices are aboui\nover. Some that have resisted de\ndines so far may still be compelled\nby the law of supply and demand re\nproper level\nsultant on the refusal of the public\nto buy at high prices, to come down\nto a lower level. Some that have\nbeen unduly depressed to a p' int\nwhere production cost and a rea^on\nable profit are no longer obtainable\nwill come under the same law be\ncau*e the supply will diminish\nthrough non-productioa until the\nreached. Then we\nrnay look for\nstablization \"f prices\nand a new era of business prosperity\nand wealth production. We note in\nrecent dispatches that Congress wiii\nseek to help certain producers to\nbring about such rising prices. We\nhope they will if they can, but we\nj have more faith in economic law to\nI effect this result than we have in\ncongressional law. However, a good\ncongressional law. However, a good\nj\nj\n\nhope that their confidence in law as\na remedy will get more speedy and\neffective realization that it did when\nthe law was involked to cut down\nprices and lower the cost of living,\nOPINIONS OF OTHERS\nHere's Optimistic View.\nOf course, there may be some\ndrawbacks to prohibition, but it has\ncertainly stopped a lot of men from\ntrying to sing.\u2014Dallas News.\nWell, He'll Need Charmed Life.\nGeneral Obregon is said to bear\na charmed life. If his luck holds\ngood he may last a few years as\npresident of Mexico.\u2014Birmingham\nAge-Herald.\nAre Stronger Words in Language.\nA leading Canadian Judge terms\nthe parlor bolshevik a parasite, but\nmost of us wouldn't be so charitable.\n\u2014Indianapolis Star.\nFirst Time He's Tried It.\nThe old-fashioned man who could\ndrink or let it alone is now learning\nwhat it is to let it alone.\u2014Washing\nton Post.\nWe Can Only Live in Hopes.\nIs there ever going to be any kind\nof movement that is not \"opposed\"\nto something?\u2014St. Louis Globe\nDemocrat.\nDelftware of the Fourteenth century\nwas considered among the best pottery\nof its day, its quality being even beter\nthan the famous Italian pottery of the\nsame period, but ornamentation some\nwhat inferior.\nehasdg Pooc u\nB\nEST EDITORIALS\nOF THE DAY\nWHEN A STATE QUITS\nIii West Virginia there are two mili\ntant organizations, both admittedly su\nperior to the State. One is the miners'\nunion and the other is the Association of\nmine-operators. The union is armed and\nequipped for war and the operators have\nin their service private guards and gun\nwen in large numbers. A strike being in\nprogress, these hostile forces are in daii\nIy conflict, with casualties running into\nthe hundreds.\nIt might be supposed that what a\nmonnts to nothing more than domestic\ndisorder on an unusual scale would re\nceive the instant and powerful attention\nof a Commonwealth sovereign in tili\u00ab\nsphere if in no other, but instead of\ntbat we find ne lceal authorities con\nfessing their helplessness and calling\nupon the National Government for Fed\neral troops, which are now on the scene.\n\"The State is unable to cope with the\nsituation.\" says Gov. Cornwell. \"and I\nhope with all my heart that martial law\nwill be declared immediately.\"\nWest Virginia has witnessed Fonie\nhigh-handed proceedings in this direction\nin times past, and it learned or should\ni have learned that martial law is not to\np roc j a j me( j solelv because a sheriff or\na governor fails in'his duty. Martial law\nsupervenes only in time of war and in\nthe presence of the enemy, when the\ncourts are closed and the civil authors\nties dispersed.\nThe trouble in this instance is due to\nnone of these causes. From governor\ndown, the oficials of West irginia are\nall at their posts and every court is\noppn Th Hlb,il machinery of an in\nimpendent. State has not been wreck en\nj and the men sworn to keep it in motion\nhave not been driven away. What has\nhappened is that private marauders have\nassumed control, undertaking to settle\ntheir differences in defiance of law and\ntii at the Stare, which should enforce\npeace upon both factious, has shamefully\nquit the field and is begging outsiders\nto come to its rescue.\nThis is one of the border states that\nvoted overwhelmingly a few days ago for\na presidential candidate whose chief\nissue was \"Americanism\" and who held\nthat the ''internationalism\" of the\nI League of Nations would deprive us of\nour liberties. Its present Chief Magis\ntr\u00e4te and most of its people evidently\nsee nothing inconsistent with thi\nheroic attitude in their entreaty to the\n\nFederal Government to take over their\nafairs and ad ninister them upon a drum\nhead. If tli 'if demands were granted!\nthey would not nave a voice in the pro\nceilings that followed,\nCnder our system political bankrupt\ncy cannot reach more degrading lev 'is.\nj With its whole body of officials iueapa\nwith the nass of its inhabitants des\ntilude of resource, and with no military\n(iI constabulary force strong enoug.i t<\nmeet rival n'js and subdue them both.\n^at clmm has V^\u00bb ia\n\u00bbHm ai ion <s a self-governing statt\nx ew York \\V\u00bbrld (Dein.)\nHORSEBACK HALL\n\nIn \"Heartbreak House Shaw lets >ne\nj* }jj<; fxplHiti his title* jhk I\nsupplement it with the equally pungent\nphrase Horseback Hall. The former is\nthe middle-class home of modern Kng\nI&nd. One might have wished that Shaw\nhad written a companion piece under the\nsecond title, but Margot Asquith has\nsawd him the bother. In her autobio\ntcrdphy\u2014judging at least by its serialize\u00ab!\npublications\u2014she has all unconsciously\norll titP dignified\nit the space and\nand with the native of an unbelievably j\nself-satisfied woman, drawn a full-length j\nportrait of a conspicuous and typical in- j\nhabitant of Horseback Hall.\nAs such a document it would be easy\no justify the solemnity with which Lou\nIon has received this extraordinary pub\nlication. But the weeklies just arrived\nSpectator down, give j\nconsideration due u\ngreat masterpiece\u2014instead of a self-\nsevelatorv document. To an American j\nthis can'seem onlv silly. A witty and\nconceited woman who feels none of the\naud his I\nxtraord-\nj\n\u25a0ni with I\nwhich these English critics are defend-\nthe volume is the explanation given j\nordinary obligations of friendship to\nhold intimacy sacred can always write\nsuch a shocker, if she has associated\nwith conspicuous people she can always\nmake her shocker of enough general in\nterest to earn a wide reading and much\nmoney. But to call such vain glory and\ngossip literature or suggest that intimate\nlove affairs rather dully stuted have some\nartistic value because the lov\ndesired are real folk seems tu\nilia 17 blindness.\nTypical of the absurd argum\nby the critic of The New Statesman as j\nto why Mrs. Asquith. while present- j\ning all the appearances of a vaiu woman, j\nis\"not really vain. It is because she I\nreally believes in the doctrine of the!\nTo thine own self be true;\nAnd if must follow as the night the day. j\nThou canst lot then be false to any man. I\n\"That is to say.\" applies this critic!\ni \"untrue in any serious sense. though tm* j\nresult mav be wounded teelmgs and pam\nto many.\" This is not vanity \"in lite\ni ordinary sense,\" the argument continues,\nj up0 n \"a peculiar detachment which fun-j\ndamentalh takes herself for granted.\"\nj Margot Asquith wrote: \"When any one\nI leaves the room I do not ask myself if\nj they liked me, but if I liked them,\" and\nthis the critic regards as proving his\nj point. To the casual reader at this\niistance the \u25a0(\u2022mark- and especially the\npublication of it\u2014will only confirm what\nthe rest of the book lonstantly demon\nstraits, that here was a vanity not so\nmuch grandly egotistical as childish and\nI ridiculous. The echo roused in one's\n1 mind is the voice not of Napoleon but, of\nV^uchess the one who wrote such\ni ,iovHb 1o\nj Tli se Kn iish\no( 1(l( ova ble candor\nar,) W e would not conte:\nfavor of the trurhfuin\n\u2022rvant, girls\nspeak glowingly\nof the writer.\ntheir verdict in\nBut the i\ncharacter\nmore valut\neral gossip.\nconscious\nf the writer seems\nthan any amount of\nhowever accurate\nf the book,\nlation of the\n\u25a0iccniH of far!\nphem\nThe\npicture of Horseback IJall is of n life!\nnot only \"fast, furious und fashionable.\"]\nbut hard, selfish and shallow wherein\na woman of education and family can\nlive without purpose or plan, for the\npursuit, of sensation after sensation-~\nand at the end sell her sensations for\ncash. Perhaps Horseback Hall is only\na Shaw nightman. Perhaps Ma:got\nAsquith is typical of nothing sure the\ntribe of enfants terribles that belongs to\nno one era or nation. But these seem\nthe important points to discuss rather\nthan the quality of gossip which w mid\nbring a blush to the cheek of George\nMoore himself.\u2014New York Tribune,\n(Rep.)\nThe writings in the 011. Testament\nrange over a period of more than 1,000\nyears, while those fthe New Testa\nment were written almost couteinper\nancousdy.\nThe Haskln Letter\nBy FREDERIC K\ntiAShJN\nA BLOW TO CHIVALRY.\nWashington, I). C., Nov. 30.\u2014Is the\nsystem of formal courtesy with which\nmen treat women a sign of respect or\nof scorn? Does it put woman on a\npedestal, or brand her an inferior?\nThese questions are just now the sub\nject of a jjood deal of debate among\nadvanced feminists, pnd it is even possi\nble that some pronouncement on the\nsi bject may be made by a leading\nwoman's organization.\nNo longer is it safe for a man ^dis\ncriminatingly to lift his bat to a woman.\nThat is, not if she happens to be a\nfeminist of the most advanced school.\nThese radicals say that hat tipping,\nfar from signifying respect, means sim\nply that the man regards woman as a\nweak and helpless creature. They dig\nback into the romantic days of chivalry\nand produce data showing that the bold,\nbrave knights used to remove their\nweighty helmets in the presence of any\none who was to be trusted or harmless.\nWomen came in this second group.\nThere may have been other reasons why\nthe knights made a lady's presence a\nregular excuse to dispense with their\nhead cages. Probably the weight made\ntheir heads ache. Probably, too, they\nliked their feminine friends to see their\nnoble features. But the big idea, wheth\ner they were conscious of it at all\ntimes or not, was that woman was a\nflhing apart and not to be taken ser\niously.\nThe same principle, according to the\nfeminists, has come down to us in other\nbits of gallantry which in their true\nmeaning proclaim woman's inferiority.\nThis is true of a man walking on the\noutside of the pavement to guard u\nwoman against any danger from the\nstreet, and also of a man rising to give\na woman a seat in a street car.\nThe first is obviously an act of protec\ntion, based on the idea of woman's fragil\nity. Regarding street car conduct there\nis some controversy. The advance guard\nof feminism finds that when a man rises\nin a public place to resign his seat t\nwoman he is making a special tout\u00bb .--siou\nto her sex. especially her tragibtj. Ir tl c\nwoman is able-bodied, the \u00ab\u00abJ* 11\nnot exactly a compliment. i\nthey say, the pantomime ot exchanging\nposition\u00ab on a_ street car can >e e i 1\ned and social intercourse will be one s ep\nnearer au honest, sensible busis.\nfj om mfcu vhen \u201etfered on\npspecia i consideration for their sex, agr\nt j iar V(<rs 0 ften a man is to be applauded\ngiving his seat to someone eise. Com\nmon politeness -not offensive chivalry\u2014\ndrinands tluit an u!( prison of either sex.\na womaQ with a baby, a cripple, or a\nJM .rsou. should be seated iu a street\nat or waiting room. Some concede that\na jjiau can even surrender his seat to a\ntired looking woman of any age without\nimplying that \u00ablie is a mere doll to be\nhandled with care. And of course, some\nwomen sav that thev like to see a man\n.show consideration \"for them, whatever\nit implies.\nAncient ideas of woman's place in so\nu in\nttefy still guide us wueii 11 1.ooiri 10\ni\u00fcuny social fornmiitics. in some placc>\nit is stsli held the correct thing for a\nman ro precede a woman up stairs and\ndescend after by. I he origin of this is\nobscure, but we have been told that it\nFormality Versus Consideration\nMost of tile women, however, even\ntlios6 who prefer to accept tnc\nbasis of\nwith the polite\nwoman had 110\ner for a mau t\nthe illustration might romain unshatter\nod. If he descended first, and stood\nawaiting his fair companion below, either\nthe styles iu clothing\nild probably be traced to the time when\n\u2022men wore hoop skirts. This combined\ndea of the time that a\ngs, would makje it prop\nconduct himself so that\ndecorum\nuld\npre,\nup a flight of steps is obviously out oi\ndate. Recently convention has changed\nsomewhat: to allow the man to follow the\nwoman both up and downstairs.\nAnother threadbare convention is for\nthe women at a dinner party to adjou\"'\nto the parlors, leaving the men to smok'\nand talk in the dinning room. This pro\nceednre started at the medieval ban\nojiets when everybody, men aud womei\nalike crammed the neck on as many]\nkinds of food as the host could pile or.\nthe overladen board. After dinner, the\ndamsels retired, aud their lords proceed\ned to drink, themselves to sleep under\nthe table. This dinner party etiquette\nwhich was still justified until recently\nby the fact that women were supposed\nto ob.iecr to cigar smoke, is now a mere\nhollow form. Certainly few modern]\nhave had to change. Nowadays.\nwhen women's skirts are knee length\nand street car steps two feet high, the\naution of a man preceding a woman\nY ou'll \u00fcAvt*\nHAW D IT i O\n\\AJu~i\nUt S\nlike A MSVAJ Coat\nYou cawt recc\nT HE oiFF\u00dfREUCC\nV ir t C>_9 -S ay\n\u00f6i\n1\na\nCO f? fc\nwon or* p\nK A\nI'v/E a\nSWH.L lAlLOft\n\u00fc. T T 9\nCL^ssv\nSAV WHO\nis YouR\nI MLO^ v\n\u00fck\n\nWMh\nS\\V\nWilli\nWOVA> DO You L'Mfc,'\nmy wtiuu C oat\nv, CEORfiE p J\n.-s.\nm\nIT 5 -SlWtUL\nBILL W! rlcftt\nPSD VoU 6'ET\nIT\"\n7m\nm\nmm\niSlVl'T \u00cfHAT r\nTue G oods\nJ ust vuhat\ntve.\ni looking\nMdc\u00ab-i n\nYes! F or T he]\nPozenTH TIME\nPlOc,\nYoO GET I v\n0^\nGEORfiF\nI ro\nT\n\"\u00e9.\nm.\n#1\nH I\u00bb\n-A\n9\"*\n\u2022''H\nH\nd 1 r-\nT u t s C oat tS j\nSi x Ye ws <?Lt>J\nW\nm\nm\n'C2S>\nwomen object to the scent of tobacco\nsmoke, and many feel slighted if not in\nvited to help make it.\nSome Individual Views.\nThe women do not intend to keep\ntheir theories in the conversation stage.\nThere is talk here pro and con of a pub\nlic declaration to settle these matters\nof what is desireable in the way of court\nesy from men. It is in this connection\nthat the Woman's party is considering a\nbill of rights to be drafted by the national\nconvention of women voters when it\nmeets at the capital next February.\nthis would certainly simplify the situa\ntion for perplexed man. Before such a\ndeclaration could be made, however\nthere would have to be a concensus\nof opinion obtained. So faiv there has\nbeen no organized attempt to find out\nwhere the women voters stand o nthe\nquestion, though there is no doubt every\nwoman has her own definite ideas on\nthe subject.\nWe give here three sample opinions!\nby women who are representative, anu\nwe predict that the convention will have\nsome trouble iu reconciling the differ\ndiffer\nj\nj\nsome trouble iu reconciling the differ\ndiffer\nent factions which will rise to show that\nlifting a hat is an act of scorn or a ges\nture of reverence.\nMargaret Hatfield, who is a strong be\nliever in woman's equality with mau, and\nwho retains her maiden name, though\nmarried, expressed the following view:\n\"There has always been, and I sup\npose always will be chivalry which is\nfounded on women being the mothers\nof the race. Man's willingness to carry\nthe heavier burden is founded ou this\nf actual basis. But the chivalry which\ndivides women into two classes, the pro\ntpcted, and the unprotected woman, is\nintolerable, and the quicker it is done\naway with, the quicker we will approach\nreal civilization\nMargaret Hatfield found out that hat\ntipping and other ceremonies were only\nskin deep in our civilization, when she\nleft a sheltered existance to experience\nthe sensations of a bread winner in a\nI strange city. In nine weeks of the exper\nlllu\nj ment g (le half a dozen jobs, all mis\nf rab]y pai(] nud shp learned that the un\nprotected girl dosent get much in the\nway 0 f disinterested gallantry from men.\nj SJ](1 advoeates r hat man should do away\nj outworn, bothersome, formal\nj t j eg toward the women he regards as\nj worthy of his protection. In their place\nj a i( wou j ij ave }jj m adopt toward all\nW omen the same attitude of sensible\ncourtesy thst\nineiu\nuses\ndealing w'ith\nfollowed is a matter, it seems to me. of!\nthc complefest indifference to women.\nAH courtesies reflect credit upon the\nperson who offers them and nor upon the\nperson to whom they are offered. The\nj lifting of a hat is a graceful act becom\ni ing to almost any man, and if it is omit\ni ted. the man alone loses.'*\nAs for men they seem to hesitate to\nexpress their sentiments freely. Most\nif them tip their hats to the street\nand remove them in elevators, because\nA Conservative Viewpont.\nMabel Boardman, the first\nI commissioner of the District o\nj umbia. is opposed to the anti-c\nI bestowed upon women would\ni loss and not a gain,\" she told\nwoman\nof Coi\nphiv air y\nmean a\na ij aud\nlent\nlife'\nitie:\na few days ago. \"Chivalry adds to\nvalues. To dispense with auien\nwhich have become a habit, and\nare in no sense a burden, would be a\ngreat mistake.\"\nStill another attitude is taken by An\nita Pollitzer, legislative secretary of the\nwoman's party, who said thoughtfully,\nwhen questioned:\nWhether the ancient customs of cour\ntesy from men to women continue to be\n\nthey think the women expect it. Some\nprivately object to the custom on the\nj\nj\n\nj\nj\ni\nground that it is responsible for un\nj counted colds and cases of pneumonia.\nI Back in 1664 Samuel Pepys wrote into\nhis tliarv:\u2014\"Home to bed, having gut\na strange cold in my head by flinging\noff mv bead at dinner aud sitting with\nthe wind in my neck.\" And ever since,\nmen have grumbled more or less about\nexposure to drafts in the cause of\nchivalry.\nlt' Margaret Hatfield and other prog-'\nressives are right, men will soon be freed\nof hat raising responsibilities. These\nwomen hold that the cutom is slowly\ndying out anyway, and that, if enough\nwomen denounce it, it will soon be as\nobsolete as the old-fashioned bow which\nrequired lots of space and more time\nthan the modern man or woman would\ncare to give to non-essentials.\ndriuk a brew made from\nthe Brazilian mate tree a\nfor China or India tea.\nthe leavt\ns a subs'\nHydrastia Cream\nSOFTENS ROUGH SKINS\nLAPEYRE BROS. DRUG STORE\ni\nExpedition to Thibet\nJ _\nAlso Will Seek to Capture\n117:1 j Animale\nj \u00f6trange WHO Animais\u00bb,\nJ\nj Xew York\u2014The expedition sponsored\nTRIBES OF OLD ASIA\nby the American Museum of Natural His\ntory which will set forth for China next\nFebruary will search not only for fos\nsils of the ape-man, regarded by biolo\ngists as the \"missing link\" in the chain\nof evolution, but will study the aborig\ninal tribes now said to be fast disap\nj pearing in China.\nj \"We know as little about some of the\nj living natives as about the fossil history\nj 0 f the country,\" says Roy Chapman An\nf rews w 10 w jji lead the expedition,\n\"j j0 ng before the Chinese arrived, China\nj was inhabited by aboriginal tribes, which\nj were pushed south and west just as the\nj jndians were driven westward by white\nj men who advanced across the American\nI continent.\nRemnants Survive\nj \"Remnants of nearly 30 of these\n1 tribes, such as the Lolos, Mosos, Lisos\nand others, are rapidly disappearing, and\nthe expedition expects to study them be\nI fore they become extinct.\"\nDescribing these aborigines with whom\nhe has hunted. Mr. Andrews said they\nare totally unlike Chinese having tall and\nj slender bodies, long faces, patrician no\nses and other characteristics of C'auca\nsian blood.\nMr. Andrews says that scientific men\nI are now agreed in the belief that the\noldest prehistoric remains of man, and\nof many beasts, he somewhere within the\ngreat Central Asiatic Plateau, where few\nwhite men have ever penetrated.\nConcealed by Chinese\nOne of the reasons why little is known\nof China's fossils and those of interior\nAsia is that material of this sort is\nI carefully concealed by the Chinese, who\nterm the relics \"dragon's bones\" and\nj use them for medicinal purposes, said\nMr. Andrews.\ni One result expected is the education\nj of Americans in a knowledge of the im\ni mense continent across the Pacific.\nWhether success or failure meets the at\n1 tempt to find the \"missing link,\" hun\ndreds of thousands of specimens of Asi\natic animal and plant life are to be col\nlected and brought to America. These\nit is planned to place in the proposed\n$1.(KH).000 Hail of Asiatic Life in this\ncity.\nCapture Wild Animals\nCapture\nHunts for wild animals many of which\nthe explorer hopes to bring alive to the!\nUnited States will furnish excitement,\nIn a corner of the Gobi desert are herds\nof wiid horses, while on the Thibetan\nsteppes are the enormous lak. snow\nleopards and giant pandas. In China is\nthe akin, a strange ox-like ammal with\na veritable golden fleece that roams\nthe highest mountain valleys and repre\nsents an intermediate stage between the\nj antelope and the goat, says Mr. Andrews.\nHeadquarters for the exposition are\nI to be at Peking. The work of the ex\npedition is to continue for five years.\nj The first year will be d\u00ebvoted to studies\nin palaeontology and zoology in China,\nThe second year the work is to b\u00e8 car\nried into Mongolia, with geologists added\nj to the field staff. Then for the next\nj three years the entire force will be\nscattered in widespread sections of Asia,\nLake Constanct. Switzerland, is sub\nject to sudden enormous risings of its\nwaters, due to the rapid melting of snow\non adjacent mountains.\nFrench explorers in South Dakota\nj gave the name of Bad Lands to the ter\ni ritorv they discovered.\nAmerican Bank Trust\nCo. of Great Fal